). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Hywel ap Maredudd was born about 1270, in Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Maredudd ap Hywel. He married Mrs. Hywel ap Maredudd about 1295, in Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"ABT 1270–":"umbes 1270–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","1288–Female":"1288–Surnud","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","ABT 1295":"umbes 1295","1235":"1235","1288":"1288","1275":"1275","about 1288":"umbes 1288","1270":"1270","ABT 1270":"umbes 1270","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","of Pennarth,Llanystumdwy,Caernarvonshire,Wales":"Llanystumdwy, Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of Ranorshire,Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1270–":"noin 1270–Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1275–Female":"1275–Kuollut","1288–Female":"1288–Kuollut","1235–Male":"1235–Kuollut","ABT 1295":"noin 1295","1235":"1235","1288":"1288","127